{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as a pressure gauge measuring the electrical 'push' in a circuit.",
      "misconception": "Thinking a voltmeter measures the flow of electricity rather than the pressure difference."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate of flow of electric current.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as a flow meter measuring how many electrons pass a point every second.",
      "misconception": "Believing an ammeter measures the voltage or 'strength' of a battery."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure electrical resistance.",
      "anchor": "Measures how much a component 'fights' or restricts the flow of current.",
      "misconception": "Assuming you can accurately measure resistance while the circuit is still powered on."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate of electrical power being used.",
      "anchor": "Measures the 'work' being done by the circuit at a specific moment.",
      "misconception": "Confusing instantaneous power (Watts) with total energy consumed over time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument (often a kilowatt-hour meter) that measures the total electrical energy consumed over time.",
      "anchor": "The meter found in a domestic service cupboard that calculates the electricity bill.",
      "misconception": "Thinking an energy meter and a wattmeter perform the exact same function."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Voltmeter for voltage",
    "Ammeter for current",
    "Ohmmeter for resistance",
    "Wattmeter for power",
    "Energy meter for energy consumption"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using generic terms like 'tester' instead of specific instrument names",
    "Confusing the measurement of power with the measurement of energy",
    "Believing current and voltage are measured by the same instrument setting"
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Measuring Potential and Flow",
      "objective": "Identify the correct instruments for measuring voltage and current.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To measure electrical quantities accurately, you must select the instrument designed for that specific property. Voltage is the electrical 'push' or potential difference between two points in a circuit. To measure this, we use a Voltmeter.",
        "Current is the actual flow of electrons through a conductor. To measure the rate of this flow, we use an Ammeter. The 'A' in Ammeter relates to Amperes, which is the unit for current.",
        "It is important to distinguish between the pressure (Voltage) and the flow (Current). While modern digital multimeters can often do both, you must select the correct mode: Voltmeter for potential difference and Ammeter for flow. Using the wrong setting can result in blown fuses in the meter or incorrect readings."
      ],
      "hint": "Think of the units: Volts are measured by a Voltmeter, and Amps are measured by an Ammeter."
    },
    {
      "title": "Measuring Resistance and Power",
      "objective": "Identify the correct instruments for measuring resistance and electrical power.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Resistance is the property of a component that restricts or 'fights' the flow of electricity. We measure this opposition using an Ohmmeter. The name comes directly from the unit of resistance, which is the Ohm.",
        "Electrical Power is the rate at which a circuit does work or converts energy. This is an instantaneous measurement of how much 'effort' the circuit is exerting at that exact moment. To measure electrical power, we use a Wattmeter.",
        "A common mistake is confusing the 'fight' (Resistance) with the 'work' (Power). Always remember: use an Ohmmeter to check how much a wire resists flow, and use a Wattmeter to see how much power a load, like a heater or motor, is consuming."
      ],
      "hint": "The instrument name usually contains the unit it measures, such as 'Ohm' or 'Watt'."
    },
    {
      "title": "Measuring Electrical Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the instrument used for measuring electrical energy over time.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electrical Energy is distinct from Power because it includes the element of time. While a Wattmeter shows you the power being used right now, Energy represents the total amount of electricity consumed over a duration.",
        "To measure this total consumption, we use an Energy Meter, which is often specifically called a Kilowatt-hour meter (kWh meter). This is the instrument you will find at the service head of a house or building to track usage for billing.",
        "Think of it like a car: a Wattmeter is like the speedometer showing your current speed (Power), while the Energy Meter is like the odometer showing the total distance traveled (Energy)."
      ],
      "hint": "Energy is power multiplied by time; look for the meter that tracks total usage, like the one in a domestic cupboard."
    },
    {
      "title": "Instrument Selection Criteria",
      "objective": "Match the specific electrical quantity to its internationally recognised measuring instrument.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Professional electricians must use precise technical terminology. Instead of using generic terms like 'tester' or 'meter,' you must identify the specific instrument required for the task as per assessment criteria 202.LO2.AC2.3.",
        "The relationship is direct: Resistance is measured by an Ohmmeter, Power by a Wattmeter, Current by an Ammeter, and Voltage by a Voltmeter. Energy, which is power used over time, is measured by an Energy Meter.",
        "Selecting the correct instrument ensures the internal circuitry of the meter is matched to the quantity. For example, an Ammeter is designed with very low resistance to allow flow, while a Voltmeter has very high resistance to measure pressure without drawing current. Using the correct name ensures you are using the correct physical tool for the job."
      ],
      "hint": "Match the quantity (like Voltage) to the instrument named after its unit (like Voltmeter)."
    }
  ]
}

